data.content:
In xUnit, there are no setup/teardown attributes. Instead, it uses **constructor/`IDisposable`** for per-test lifecycle and **`IClassFixture<T>`** for one-time class-level lifecycle:

```csharp
public class DatabaseFixture : IAsyncLifetime
{
    public Task InitializeAsync()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }

    public Task DisposeAsync()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp]
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable replaces [TearDown]
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + `IAsyncLifetime.InitializeAsync` |
| `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + `IAsyncLifetime.DisposeAsync` |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |
| `Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)` | `Assert.NotNull(x)` |
| `Assert.That(x, Is.EqualTo(y))` | `Assert.Equal(y, x)` ← expected first |

The constructor runs fresh **before each test** and `Dispose` runs **after each**, matching NUnit's `[SetUp]`/`[TearDown]` semantics. The `DatabaseFixture` is created once and shared across all tests in the class.
